Gel Labeler is a self-contained, offline-capable browser tool for annotating SDS-PAGE and other gel electrophoresis images for publication. Open the HTML file directly in Chrome — no installation, no internet connection, no data leaves your computer.

What it does:

Upload a gel image (PNG, JPG, TIFF, BMP), crop and rotate it, set well positions by dragging across the gel, label each lane, place molecular weight markers from a preset ladder or manually, add a title and experiment metadata, annotate bands with custom text, and export — either as a flat PNG/JPEG or as a fully editable PowerPoint slide where every label, kDa number, title, and legend entry is an independent text box you can reposition and restyle in PowerPoint without touching the original image.

Key features:

Supports TIFF files including multi-page and 16-bit
Sequential ladder placement — select a preset (PageRuler, NEB, Bio-Rad, or your own saved presets), then click each band on the gel in order; skip invisible bands with one button
Band size calculator — click any unknown band after placing ladder markers to get an estimated molecular weight by log-linear Rf interpolation
Lane legend displayed as a column to the right of the gel, colour-matched to well labels
All settings (well labels, ladder bands, fonts, colours, presets) saved automatically between sessions
Fully offline — PptxGenJS and UTIF decoder are embedded inside the single HTML file
